messages.message:
Patch Set 3:

> (1 comment)

After further investigation, I can say that Lustre properly saves the "security.c" xattr, by using the numeric xattr type LDISKFS_XATTR_INDEX_SECURITY and the name "c". I traced this in the code and could see that ldiskfs_xattr_security_set() is called with name="c" when creating a new encrypted file. This is confirmed by a dump of the inode with debugfs:

   # debugfs -R "inode_dump -x <266>" /var/loop/mdt1
   [snip]
   offset = 44 (0054), name_len = 1, name_index = 6
   value_offset = 740 (1350), value_inum = 0, value_size = 40
   name = c
   value = <hexdump>
   0000  0201 0403 0000 0000 f971 6392 aef7 e3aa  .........qc.....
   0020  1592 645a 44d4 797a e392 ab6e 646d f9af  ..dZD.yz...ndm..
   0040  f974 7808 5134 3e78                      .tx.Q4>x


And we have:

   #define LDISKFS_XATTR_INDEX_SECURITY	        6


Now, digging into e2fsprogs code, the function read_encryption_xattr() looks suspicious. It calls ext2fs_xattrs_read() and then ext2fs_xattr_get() for the name "c", but as the code extract below shows, ext2fs_xattrs_read() puts the fully qualified xattr name in x->name, i.e. including the prefix string:

   		/* Extract name */
   		prefix = find_ea_prefix(entry->e_name_index);
   		prefix_len = (prefix ? strlen(prefix) : 0);
   		err = ext2fs_get_memzero(entry->e_name_len + prefix_len + 1,
   					 &x->name);
   		if (err)
   			return err;
   		if (prefix)
   			memcpy(x->name, prefix, prefix_len);
   		if (entry->e_name_len)
   			memcpy(x->name + prefix_len,
   			       (char *)entry + sizeof(*entry),
   			       entry->e_name_len);
   		x->short_name = x->name + prefix_len;
   		x->name_index = entry->e_name_index;

What makes read_encryption_xattr() suspicious is also the fact that all the other callers of ext2fs_xattr_get() call it with the fully prefixed xattr name.

So I think I should fix read_encryption_xattr() in patch #45212, instead of adding a Lustre specific case.
